Lab Report Number 1

Option 1: Run a trend analysis

I am going to look at the trends in peoples worry about losing their jobs. Specifically, respondents are asked: Thinking about the next 12 months, how likely do you think it is that you will lose your job or be laid off very likely, fairly likely, not too likely, or not at all likely? (1) Very likely, (2) Fairly likely, (3) Not too likely, (4) Not at all likely?

Install packages and open GSStrends.csv

library(data.table)
library(QMSS)
vars <- c("joblose", "year", "degree")  ## I am going to look at year and education
sub = data.table::fread("/Users/hengyuai/Desktop/TS/Lab1/trends-gss.csv",
                        sep = ",",
                        select = vars)
library(plyr)
library(ggplot2)

Recode variables to make it easier to interpret

sub = na.omit(sub) ## the analysis will require complete cases and no missings on any of these values
sub$worry = ifelse(sub$joblose <= 2, 1, 0) ## recode "jobloss", it is 1 if you are worried about losing your job
sub[sub$degree < 5] ## delete the "DK" and "NA" answer in the degree column
sub$hiedu = ifelse(sub$degree >= 3, 1, 0) ## recode "degree", you got higher education if you received a bachelor or graduate degree

Show the distribution of the answer

Tab(sub$worry)
##   Count   Pct Cum.Pct
## 0 16708 89.14   89.14
## 1  2036 10.86  100.00

This indicates that for all of the years, about 10.86% of respondents were worried about losing their jobs (Answer #1 and #2).

Get mean of worry by year using ddply from plyr package

by.year = ddply(sub, "year", summarise, mean = mean(worry))
{plot(by.year, type = "l", lwd = 2, col = "navyblue", bty ="l") ## plot the trend
with(by.year, abline(line(year, mean), col = "maroon", lwd = 2, lty = 2))} ## add a fitted line

From the graph, we can clearly see that the extent of peoples worry about losing job has changed across time. People were less worried in the earlier period, from roughly 1973 until the 2002. After 2005, people became more pessimistic about their jobs.

OLS Regression

I would like to develop a regression model that would capture the dynamics of peoples worry about their jobs. As a default, I will fit a linear model, where year is entered in as a linear term. The model is below:

lm.worry1 = lm(worry ~ year, sub)
summary(lm.worry1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = worry ~ year, data = sub)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -0.1131 -0.1101 -0.1083 -0.1058  0.8957

## Coefficients:

## (Intercept) -0.3902785  0.4485946  -0.870    0.384
## year         0.0002502  0.0002250   1.112    0.266
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.3112 on 18742 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  6.599e-05,  Adjusted R-squared:  1.264e-05 
## F-statistic: 1.237 on 1 and 18742 DF,  p-value: 0.2661

This model shows that with each year that passes, peoples worry increased, on average, by 0.000247 points it is not statistically significant (p > 0.1). The Adjusted Rsquared from this model is 6.432e-05, which is quite low. Also, in the graph above, it is not hard to see that the linear fit line misses most of the ups and downs of the trend.

Consider a quadratic fit

lm.worry2 = lm(worry ~ year + I(year^2), sub)

Graph the cubic trend

by.year.q = ggplot(by.year, aes(x = year, y = mean)) + geom_line(color = "navyblue") ## plot the trend
by.year.q + stat_smooth(methiod = "lm", formular = y ~ poly(x,3), color = "maroon", se = F, lty = 2) ## add a cubic fitted line
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The graph above shows the trend of peoples worry of losing job. This cubic fit line better catches the ups and downs of the trend than the linear fit line in the first graph.

Graph trend over time by degree

by.year.edu = ddply(sub, c("year", "hiedu"), summarise, mean = mean(worry, na.rm = T))
plot_by_year_edu = ggplot(by.year.edu, aes(x = year, y = mean, group = hiedu, color = factor(hiedu))) + geom_point() + geom_line() + scale_color_manual(values = c("navyblue", "darkmagenta"), labels = c("not receive high education", " receive high education"), name = "") ## plot the trend
plot_by_year_edu + stat_smooth(method = "lm", formula = y ~ poly(x,3), se = F, lty = 2) # add cubic fit lines

The graph above is the trend of peoples worry of losing job, divided by their education. We can see that people with high education were less worried than people with lower education level. But it seems that those two groups of people follow a very similar pattern.
